No, I'm a... I'm a mango chicken.
I've decided I want to be a mango chicken.

246
00:10:48,200 --> 00:10:51,960
Yeah, so basically, I'm fire,
and he's water.

247
00:10:52,040 --> 00:10:55,560
And together, fire and water,
things get steamy.

248
00:10:55,640 --> 00:10:57,040
[laughs] That's true.

249
00:10:57,120 --> 00:10:58,760
[laughs]

250
00:10:58,840 --> 00:10:59,960
That's very naughty.

251
00:11:00,040 --> 00:11:01,040
Yes, it is.

252
00:11:03,280 --> 00:11:07,560
[narrator] <i>For Ruth and Thomas,</i>
<i>finding love has led to independence.</i>

253
00:11:07,640 --> 00:11:10,600
<i>They moved in together
just over a year ago.</i>

254
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:12,840
[Ruth] This is my card collection.

255
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:14,160
This here's thick.

256
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:16,240
So it's quite heavy.

257
00:11:16,880 --> 00:11:21,360
This is one of my favorite sections,
which is food.

258
00:11:21,880 --> 00:11:24,200
- [man] So you collect business cards?
- [Ruth] Yes, I do.

259
00:11:24,280 --> 00:11:26,080
[man] What's your guess
at how many you have?

260
00:11:26,160 --> 00:11:28,600
How many? Um, probably thousands.

261
00:11:28,680 --> 00:11:29,680
Look, there's...

262
00:11:30,760 --> 00:11:32,560
This is a lot.

263
00:11:33,920 --> 00:11:36,080
I can't wait to sort them all out.

264
00:11:36,160 --> 00:11:38,960
[man] I don't think I've ever met anyone
who collects business cards.

265
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,040
Well, autistic people are known
for being pretty unusual.

266
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:44,240
[grunts]

267
00:11:55,960 --> 00:11:57,480
[Thomas] This is my garden railway.

268
00:11:57,560 --> 00:11:59,320
[train whistling]

269
00:11:59,400 --> 00:12:01,840
A garden is your own idea of heaven.

270
00:12:03,920 --> 00:12:06,320
So, of course, mine's gonna have
a train running through it.

271
00:12:08,600 --> 00:12:10,360
[man] When did you guys first meet?

272
00:12:10,440 --> 00:12:15,680
My sister told me that, um,
she knew another aspie at church,

273
00:12:16,080 --> 00:12:17,680
and, uh, she wanted me to meet him,

274
00:12:17,760 --> 00:12:19,320
because she thought
we'd become friends.

275
00:12:19,400 --> 00:12:21,360
We immediately understood each other.

276
00:12:21,440 --> 00:12:23,160
We... And I actually...

277
00:12:23,240 --> 00:12:25,760
When we first met each other,
I wrote in my journal,

278
00:12:25,840 --> 00:12:28,000
- "Oh, I want to marry this guy."
- [laughs]

279
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:29,400
I didn't know that.

280
00:12:29,480 --> 00:12:31,040
That's true. I told you that before.

281
00:12:36,200 --> 00:12:37,200
[man] Likes her milk.

282
00:12:38,400 --> 00:12:40,080
That's why I need to go buy some.

283
00:12:42,160 --> 00:12:43,840
[man] What's that picture on the fridge?

284
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:45,440
- That one?
- [man] Hmm.

285
00:12:45,520 --> 00:12:47,720
Ruth drew that for my birthday.

286
00:12:47,800 --> 00:12:49,160
"Happy birthday, Tom,

287
00:12:49,240 --> 00:12:50,880
from your crazy girlfriend Ruthy."

288
00:12:50,960 --> 00:12:53,160
And then that is, um, runes.

289
00:12:53,480 --> 00:12:55,240
[Ruth] Can't wait to marry you.

290
00:12:55,320 --> 00:12:57,080
I love you, Ruth.

291
00:12:57,160 --> 00:12:58,200
Apparently, it says that.

292
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,080
If I actually was dating somebody,

293
00:13:10,160 --> 00:13:13,280
and I actually entered a relationship,
and then eventually...

294
00:13:14,640 --> 00:13:15,640
married her,

295
00:13:16,120 --> 00:13:19,000
I would treat her as my top priority.

296
00:13:19,080 --> 00:13:24,120
She would be pretty much my most valuable
and greatest treasure of all time.

297
00:13:24,200 --> 00:13:27,080
She'd practically be my million dollars.

298
00:13:30,120 --> 00:13:32,640
- [mother] Mike, can you get me some salt?
- [Michael] Yeah.

299
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:37,760
- You mean the sea salt?
- Yep. Please.

300
00:13:37,840 --> 00:13:41,080
[man] Why do you think Michael's
finding it hard to meet someone?

301
00:13:41,160 --> 00:13:44,680
I think he just needs to find somebody
that's like-minded.

302
00:13:45,840 --> 00:13:48,280
I don't think he wants anybody loud.

303
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:49,960
Or gothic.

304
00:13:50,400 --> 00:13:52,000
- Mm-hmm.
- [Michael] Or tomboyish.

305
00:13:52,080 --> 00:13:52,920
Mm-hmm.

306
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:56,320
Or practically any girl that acts like...
like she's still in high school.

307
00:13:56,720 --> 00:13:58,680
Yeah. Sounds right.

308
00:13:58,760 --> 00:14:00,920
If she's the right person for me, then...

309
00:14:01,360 --> 00:14:04,160
I'll... I'll consider proposing to her.

310
00:14:04,640 --> 00:14:07,360
- Okay.
- By coincidence, I've already decided

311
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:09,600
on the perfect wedding ring
for my partner.

312
00:14:10,880 --> 00:14:13,000
In the form of a crown...

313
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:16,960
to signify that she'll be my queen,
per se.

314
00:14:17,720 --> 00:14:22,360
But I'm not really too keen on kids
at the moment, because... [inhales]

315
00:14:22,800 --> 00:14:26,800
I have a feeling that having children
will ruin my chances of becoming wealthy.

316
00:14:27,800 --> 00:14:29,600
They kinda do. [laughs]

317
00:14:29,680 --> 00:14:32,240
But what if you meet a girl
that wants to have children,

318
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:34,560
and you're like,
"Oh, but that's gonna take away

319
00:14:34,640 --> 00:14:36,720
from my bank account."
What are you gonna do?

320
00:14:36,800 --> 00:14:40,360
I'll simply tell her, "Okay,
I'll allow it, but on one condition.

321
00:14:40,440 --> 00:14:43,040
I get a vasectomy after the second child."

322
00:14:43,840 --> 00:14:44,840
Okay.

323
00:14:45,320 --> 00:14:47,480
I've been single for 25 years.

324
00:14:47,560 --> 00:14:50,760
I'm not too willing to be single
for another 25.

325
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:52,240
What if you are?

326
00:14:52,320 --> 00:14:53,320
Mum.

327
00:14:53,520 --> 00:14:55,440
I still refuse to take that for an answer.

328
00:14:55,520 --> 00:14:58,480
But it's not an answer. I'm just saying,
it's a hypothetical what-if.

329
00:14:58,560 --> 00:14:59,960
Not what if. It <i>will.</i>

330
00:15:00,040 --> 00:15:01,360
Okay. That's it.

331
00:15:01,440 --> 00:15:03,200
Not what if. It will.

332
00:15:03,280 --> 00:15:04,760
[mother] It will. Okay.

333
00:15:05,200 --> 00:15:06,800
It will. [laughs]

334
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:10,960
[narrator] <i>To help him</i>
<i>in his search for love,</i>

335
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:13,360
<i>Michael is meeting Jodi Rogers,</i>

336
00:15:13,440 --> 00:15:16,920
<i>a relationship specialist
who works with people on the spectrum.</i>

337
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:19,280
[Jodi] When they're children,
there's a lot of support

338
00:15:19,360 --> 00:15:20,840
given to people with autism

339
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:23,200
about social skill and social interaction.

340
00:15:23,280 --> 00:15:25,440
And I think when people reach adulthood,

341
00:15:25,520 --> 00:15:29,840
and they're really looking
for intimate relationships,

342
00:15:29,920 --> 00:15:32,840
I think that we don't give
a lot of support to understanding

343
00:15:32,920 --> 00:15:35,040
- the really great complexity...
- [knocking]

344
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:36,680
...of flirting with somebody else,

345
00:15:36,760 --> 00:15:39,920
or how do we develop an intimate
relationship with somebody else?

346
00:15:40,560 --> 00:15:41,760
- Hello.
- [Jodi] Hello.

347
00:15:41,840 --> 00:15:42,760
You must be Jodi.

348
00:15:42,840 --> 00:15:44,800
- [Jodi] Yes, hello. Are you Michael?
- Yes, I am.

349
00:15:45,360 --> 00:15:49,240
[Jodi] Where do people meet each other
when they're on the autism spectrum?

350
00:15:49,320 --> 00:15:51,640
People go onto sort of
a mainstream dating site,

351
00:15:51,720 --> 00:15:53,920
and then do you out yourself
as being on the spectrum,

352
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:55,000
which is really complex?

353
00:15:55,560 --> 00:15:57,520
[Michael] I've never had a partner before.

354
00:15:57,600 --> 00:16:00,960
I've always had some trouble
trying to find a partner.

355
00:16:01,440 --> 00:16:03,000
Why do you think that is?

356
00:16:03,080 --> 00:16:05,920
Well, a lot of girls
that I've been friends with in the past,

357
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:09,880
a... a lot of those friendships
have turned out to be quite... [inhales]

358
00:16:10,440 --> 00:16:11,840
disappointing.

359
00:16:11,920 --> 00:16:15,600
Do you have trouble with understanding
another person's body language?

360
00:16:15,680 --> 00:16:17,040
I have very little trouble.

361
00:16:17,800 --> 00:16:20,280
Facial expressions
always give something away.

362
00:16:20,360 --> 00:16:22,240
That's great.
It's excellent that you say that.

363
00:16:22,320 --> 00:16:26,720
Because some people on the spectrum,
they really have difficulty with that.

364
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:27,720
So that's excellent

365
00:16:27,800 --> 00:16:30,120
- that you've got that ability to do that.
- Yeah. Yes.

366
00:16:30,200 --> 00:16:32,280
When I'm with somebody,
if they're trying to mask...

367
00:16:32,360 --> 00:16:33,520
mask something...

368
00:16:33,600 --> 00:16:35,160
- [mother] He knows.
- ...on their face,

369
00:16:35,200 --> 00:16:36,680
I'll just simply say,

370
00:16:36,760 --> 00:16:39,760
mask it all you want,
but I know what you're actually feeling.

371
00:16:39,840 --> 00:16:40,720
- [mother] Yes!
- Really?

372
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:43,240
He... And you know what,
he's so good at it.

373
00:16:43,320 --> 00:16:46,520
He's so... Even with people he's just met.

374
00:16:46,600 --> 00:16:49,160
I've been studying human behavior
for many years.

375
00:16:49,240 --> 00:16:50,640
That's excellent, Michael.

376
00:16:50,720 --> 00:16:53,160
- Specifically in women.
- Yeah.

377
00:16:53,240 --> 00:16:54,160
- [laughs]
- Oh.

378
00:16:54,240 --> 00:16:57,640
It's because I've always taken
a bit of an interest in it,

379
00:16:57,720 --> 00:16:59,120
in a... in a strange way.

380
00:16:59,200 --> 00:17:02,520
No, that's not strange. Do you know what,
if you're on the autism spectrum,

381
00:17:02,600 --> 00:17:05,080
and you find body language difficult,

382
00:17:05,160 --> 00:17:08,280
actually studying body language

383
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:10,760
is a really important thing to do.

384
00:17:11,120 --> 00:17:14,280
I was told that nonverbal cues,
he'll never be able to get.

385
00:17:14,360 --> 00:17:15,960
Excuse me, nonverbal cues?

386
00:17:16,040 --> 00:17:17,440
Look at his gift.

387
00:17:17,840 --> 00:17:19,400
I was told, "Oh, you know,

388
00:17:19,480 --> 00:17:23,200
you'll... you'll probably never
hear him say I love you."

389
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:26,800
They said he probably won't have
any empathy for others.

390
00:17:27,320 --> 00:17:29,440
Biggest bunch of rubbish I ever heard.

391
00:17:29,520 --> 00:17:31,840
It's just a difference
in the way that they do things.

392
00:17:31,920 --> 00:17:33,280
They're just different, that's it.

393
00:17:33,360 --> 00:17:36,560
And people with autism
have incredible affection...

394
00:17:36,640 --> 00:17:38,280
- [mother] Yes.
- ...and deep love.

395
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:41,120
- Yes!
- [Jodi] Really wanting to connect.

396
00:17:41,200 --> 00:17:43,896
When people talk to Michael,
they might find him a bit of an oddball,

397
00:17:43,920 --> 00:17:45,280
a bit quirky, and stuff like that.

398
00:17:45,320 --> 00:17:47,880
But the thing is, we've raised him
and taught him... [inhales]

399
00:17:47,960 --> 00:17:50,640
to be confident with himself,
and that, you know what?

400
00:17:50,720 --> 00:17:53,256
Even as so-called "normal people,"
we don't have all the answers.

401
00:17:53,280 --> 00:17:57,880
But you two have obviously done
a really, really fantastic job as parents.

402
00:17:57,960 --> 00:17:59,480
They haven't given me everything.

403
00:17:59,560 --> 00:18:01,520
Not everything, but plenty.

404
00:18:01,600 --> 00:18:04,240
- [parents laugh]
- Which is still adequate.

405
00:18:04,640 --> 00:18:05,880
Which is still adequate?

406
00:18:05,960 --> 00:18:07,280
- [Michael] Yes.
- [Jodi] Yep.

407
00:18:07,360 --> 00:18:09,800
What's the difference between...

408
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:12,120
friendship and a girlfriend?

409
00:18:12,200 --> 00:18:13,880
Girlfriends, they're more serious,

410
00:18:13,960 --> 00:18:15,200
it's more intimate,

411
00:18:15,520 --> 00:18:17,760
and there's no hands-to-yourself business.

412
00:18:17,840 --> 00:18:19,456
- [parents laugh]
- Okay, hang on, hang on.

413
00:18:19,480 --> 00:18:20,960
- So, it's more...
- Because that's...

414
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:23,000
[Jodi] Tell me the difference.
It's more serious...

415
00:18:23,040 --> 00:18:24,360
What do you mean by more serious?

416
00:18:24,440 --> 00:18:26,256
- [Michael] When I say serious...
- [Jodi] Yeah.

417
00:18:26,280 --> 00:18:28,200
- ...you make the decision to...
- Yeah.

418
00:18:28,280 --> 00:18:31,440
- [father laughing]
- ...to kiss each other or, um...

419
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:33,200
We don't talk to Mum and Dad
about kissing,

420
00:18:33,240 --> 00:18:34,080
- do we?
- [mother] No.

421
00:18:34,160 --> 00:18:35,640
[sighs] N-Not... Not really.

422
00:18:35,720 --> 00:18:37,576
- I never really thought about that.
- [laughter]

423
00:18:37,600 --> 00:18:39,160
Because, you see, I've never...

424
00:18:39,240 --> 00:18:42,760
never had any interest in having...
in having sexual intercourse as...

425
00:18:42,840 --> 00:18:44,080
if you will. Um...

426
00:18:44,160 --> 00:18:46,240
- Okay, this is where I exit. [laughs]
- [Jodi] Yeah.

427
00:18:46,320 --> 00:18:49,280
I have to say,
that could be a good time. [laughs]

428
00:18:49,360 --> 00:18:52,280
Thanks very much for coming.
We'll leave you guys to it.

429
00:18:53,400 --> 00:18:55,840
And, like, one of my philosophies is,

430
00:18:56,280 --> 00:18:59,000
never fall for a girl
just because she's hot.

431
00:18:59,080 --> 00:19:01,080
I think that's an excellent philosophy.

432
00:19:01,160 --> 00:19:02,800
- I made that up myself.
- Did you?

433
00:19:02,880 --> 00:19:04,040
[laughs]

434
00:19:04,120 --> 00:19:05,920
It's a good... It's a very good one.

435
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:07,840
So, when we're going on a first date,

436
00:19:07,920 --> 00:19:09,960
what we're doing
is we're trying to find out

437
00:19:10,040 --> 00:19:13,120
have we got enough things in...

438
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:14,200
- ...common.
- ...common.

439
00:19:14,720 --> 00:19:16,800
What would be one thing
that you can think of

440
00:19:16,880 --> 00:19:18,800
if you could make a girlfriend,

441
00:19:18,880 --> 00:19:21,160
what would be something that you're into

442
00:19:21,240 --> 00:19:22,520
and that she's into?

443
00:19:22,600 --> 00:19:24,880
[Michael] There is a hobby
that I enjoy doing.

444
00:19:24,960 --> 00:19:27,760
I actually tend to do this one in secret.

445
00:19:27,840 --> 00:19:29,040
That's toy collecting.

446
00:19:29,480 --> 00:19:32,240
[Jodi] If you don't have
enough things in common,

447
00:19:32,320 --> 00:19:33,320
what do we do?

448
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:35,640
Not bother with another date.

449
00:19:35,720 --> 00:19:37,200
We don't just give up, we keep going,

450
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:39,096
- because we just have to keep finding...
- Yeah.

451
00:19:39,120 --> 00:19:41,200
...that person that's gonna be your person

452
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:42,816
- with enough in common with you.
- Yeah.

453
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:45,680
I'd really like for you to let me know

454
00:19:45,760 --> 00:19:48,160
how you go on your dates,

455
00:19:48,240 --> 00:19:51,480
and especially to find out
if you've been able to find somebody

456
00:19:51,560 --> 00:19:54,240
- that you have common interest with.
- Okay.

457
00:19:55,080 --> 00:19:57,360
- It was lovely to meet you.
- Like... Likewise.

458
00:19:57,440 --> 00:19:58,520
Take care of yourself.

459
00:19:58,600 --> 00:19:59,920
- See ya.
- And good luck.

460
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:02,000
Thanks. Thanks for your time.

461
00:20:04,040 --> 00:20:05,640
[man] Are you open to dating people

462
00:20:05,720 --> 00:20:07,600
who might have a disability
or a condition?

463
00:20:07,680 --> 00:20:08,520
Oh, yes.

464
00:20:08,600 --> 00:20:11,840
And I think dating someone
who's on the autistic spectrum,

465
00:20:11,920 --> 00:20:15,160
or someone, you know, with disabilities
might be better.

466
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:19,000
I might... I might have, um...
be able to talk to them more about it

467
00:20:19,080 --> 00:20:21,400
and not feel like I have to be fake

468
00:20:21,480 --> 00:20:24,240
and be someone completely different.

469
00:20:27,440 --> 00:20:31,000
[narrator] <i>It's been almost two years</i>
<i>since Chloe has been on a date,</i>

470
00:20:31,080 --> 00:20:32,640
<i>but that's about to change.</i>

471
00:20:34,120 --> 00:20:34,960
Hello.

472
00:20:35,040 --> 00:20:36,240
- [father] Hello, miss.
- Yeah.

473
00:20:36,280 --> 00:20:38,960
If you need to, just, you know,
twiddle your fingers or something,

474
00:20:39,040 --> 00:20:40,640
if you're getting a little bit nervy.

475
00:20:40,720 --> 00:20:44,560
And you can always excuse yourself,
you need to powder your nose or something.

476
00:20:44,640 --> 00:20:46,920
Okay, but I don't have nose powder.

477
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:49,360
No, no. It's... It's a saying, isn't it.

478
00:20:49,440 --> 00:20:51,440
- You go for... go for a wee.
- [Chloe] Oh, okay.

479
00:20:51,520 --> 00:20:52,840
But it's not honest.

480
00:20:52,920 --> 00:20:54,960
[father] That's true. Maybe you could say,

481
00:20:55,040 --> 00:20:57,256
- I'm just gonna just pop to the bathroom.
- [Chloe] Okay.

482
00:20:57,280 --> 00:20:59,000
And you can have a little bit of time.

483
00:20:59,080 --> 00:20:59,920
- Okay.
- All right?

484
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:02,080
Just... Just ask him what he likes, and...

485
00:21:02,400 --> 00:21:04,920
boom, if there's a connection,
it's a connection.

486
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:06,640
[chuckles] Hmm.

